  "Idea": "The core idea is to develop a novel framework—Learning Invariant and Disentangled Attribute Prototypes via Causal Intervention and Language-Grounded Contrastive Regularization—that enables robust, compositional visual recognition by learning transferable component prototypes for human-annotated attributes. These prototypes are designed to be invariant to environmental confounders (e.g., background, lighting), causally disentangled from spurious correlations, and semantically aligned with natural language descriptions. The method operates in three stages: (1) Prototype learning using an inverse contrastive loss (ICL)-based objective to enforce invariance of each attribute prototype across domains; (2) Causal intervention over a reconstructed Structural Causal Model (SCM) of attributes and labels to identify and remove 'fake invariant' prototypes that appear stable in training environments but fail under distribution shift; and (3) Language-grounded contrastive regularization, where vision-language pairs (e.g., 'striped animal') are used to align visual attribute prototypes with corresponding textual embeddings in a shared space, enhancing semantic fidelity and enabling zero-shot composition. \n\nThis framework allows for the construction of representations for novel classes through linear or nonlinear combinations of pretrained attribute prototypes—e.g., synthesizing a representation for 'blue-striped frog' by combining the prototypes for 'blue', 'striped', and 'frog'—even if no such instance has been observed. The system is evaluated on few-shot and zero-shot classification tasks under domain shift, with emphasis on measuring both classification accuracy and prototype disentanglement/invariance. Applications include fine-grained recognition, robotic perception with open-vocabulary understanding, and accessible AI systems that follow natural language instructions involving unseen object compositions.\n\nKey innovations include: (a) treating attribute proto